Answer 1.1, Baseline (4p)¶

  • Dense network, at least 3 layers, shaped like a pyramid
    • Last layer: 10 nodes, sigmoid.
    • Loss: categorical cross-entropy. Metric: accuracy
  • No preprocessing, regularization. Get at least 70% accuracy.
  • Explain design decisions. Discuss performance.
    • Does it overfit (large/growing gap between loss and val_loss)?
I started off with a baseline of 3 dense layers (128,64,32), with RMSprop optimizer. Then I tried out combinations of 3 to 9 layers with varying numbers of nodes (between 4 and 3072). I tested 'wider' or 'narrower' pyramids. Eventually most of my tries were at 60 to 70% accuracy after 10 to 20 epochs, but never better. Then I tried different optimizers: SGD and 25 epochs led to over 80% accuracy.  (length: 401)

def build_model_1_1():
  
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Reshape((3072,), input_shape=(32,32,3)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='relu'))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer='sgd',
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 1.2, Preprocess (2p)¶

  • Convert images to greyscale, other preprocessing optional.
    • Input shape should be (32,32,1)
  • Explain design decisions. Is it better? Why (not)?
    • Color information is likely not so useful for classification. Greyscale makes the network smaller, less parameters to learn, less likely to overfit.
I preprocessed the data with the helper function, and changed the input shape accordingly. The performance seems to have improved, accuracy is a few percent higher for most of the epochs. The loss is also quite a bit lower. I think this can be explained by the fact that color (in general) should not matter when it comes to identifying a digit, so by converting to greyscale we essentially did noise removal. I tried values of l2 regulazation, and lowering the value gave improvement. I also tried a different learning rates and played around batch size (but higher batch size lowered performance). Accuracy went up on the first few epochs if I upped the learning rate, but default learning rate caught up at later epochs. Compared to epoch 25 of my earlier models, lowering the learning rate decreased performance.  (length: 408)

def build_model_1_3():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Reshape((1024,), input_shape=(32,32,1)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(1024, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(200, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(lr=0.01),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
The convolutional layers go a long when it comes to increasing performance, but they do slow things down. Therefore I removed some of the dense layers from the previous model and added maxpooling layers which help to speed up the training, which allowed me to try out more options in a reasonable timeframe. I managed to get over 98% accuracy within 25 epochs. Changing learning rate did not lead to improvements. At this point there was overfitting so I used a dropout layer to minimize overfitting succesfully (though this decreased the general accuracy slightly). But I was then able to increase the learning rate to increase accuracy within 25 epochs without negative side effects.  (length: 687)

def build_model_2_1():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32, 32, 1)))
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
  model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.25))
  model.add(layers.Flatten())
  model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(lr=0.02),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small
    • Large shifts and rotations distort the image too much
  • Explain what you did and why. Discuss the performance of the model.
I first tested the types of augmentations seperately to find what works. Flipping lowered accuracy, since the images are in correct horizontal orientation already. Then I added a combination of the ones that had the most promising results. Shifting seemed to make help combat overfitting, because it may make the model more resistant to variations. Shearing and rotations showed similar effects. If I used too many (drastic) augmentations that seemed to cause underfitting.  (length: 475)

Answer 3.1, Misclassifications (2p)¶

  • Report the test score (on the held-out test data)
    • Should be similar to score of previous model
  • Plot confusion matrix, discuss which classes are often confused.
    • class 1 and 2 are most often confused
  • Visualize the misclassifications in more depth by focusing on a single class
  • Analyse which kinds of mistakes are made for that class.
    • Should contain some insight (e.g. misclassifications when the numbers are curly or noisy)
From the confusion matrix I noticed that 6 is confused for 8 often, so I zoomed in on that issue in the second function. I tested other numbers too and found many different causes for misclassification, including: extreme zoom or pixelation, number not viewed from straight ahead, number cramped between other numbers, number is not fully visible, there is motion blur, a shadow falls on the number, an unusual font is used, or numbers I would have misclassified myself (little hope to improve on those). Answer 4.1, Fast feature extraction (5p)¶

  • Import the VGG16 model, pretrained on ImageNet
  • Freeze convolutional base, adds a dense layer
  • Consider unfreezing the last few convolutional layers and evaluate whether that works better
    • Check if they do. It is very likely to help.
  • Discuss the observed performance
    • Should get around 80% accuracy
The model was not performing well with the fully frozen base for me. It got up to 50% rapidly but then fell off compared to my older models. Then I decided to unfreeze the last 4 layers (2 convolutional and 2 maxpooling). This improved the performance greatly. Now I got 70% accuracy within the second epoch and 80% after the 5th. If I unfreeze 2 more layers the accuracy is over 80% in just 2 epochs. The drawback is that training is slower the more layers you unfreeze, and I also got more overfitting (which I tried to combat with regularization and dropout).  (length: 564)

def build_model_4_1():
  model = models.Sequential()
  model.add(conv_base)
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Flatten())
  model.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)))
  model.add(layers.Dropout(0.2))
  model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='sigmoid'))
  for layer in conv_base.layers[0:15]:
     layer.trainable = False
  model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.SGD(lr=0.01),
                loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                metrics=['accuracy'])
  return model

I made a function that loads or stores the embedding based on whether it has been stored already. I let the pipeline function return a very simple svm pipeline, which takes a few minutes to train. The evaluate pipeline function reshapes the input data, then fits and predicts the relevant sets and returns the accuracy. evaluation_4_2 first embeds, then evaluates and returns the accuracy. def store_embeddings():
  """ Stores all necessary embeddings to file
  """
  #check if the embedding already exists, if so, load it.
  if os.path.exists(os.path.join(base_dir, 'train'+'_embedding.p')) :
    train_embedding = load_embedding("train")
    test_embedding = load_embedding("test")
  #otherwise, create it
  else :
    train_embedding = conv_base.predict(X_train)
    test_embedding = conv_base.predict(X_test)
    store_embedding(train_embedding, "train")
    store_embedding(test_embedding, "test")
  return train_embedding, test_embedding

def evaluation_4_2(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
  """ Runs 'evaluate_pipeline' with embedded versions of the input data 
  and returns the accuracy.
  """
  Xe_train, Xe_test = store_embeddings()
  acc = evaluate_pipeline(pipeline, Xe_train, y_train, Xe_test, y_test)
  return acc
